\b\fs40 \cf0 Chapter 2\
Background and Literature Review\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb240\qj

\b0\fs22 \cf0 In this chapter we will provide contextual information on the issue of fossil fuel dependence as well as the application of renewable energy sources in public buildings in the U.S. This chapter also includes an explanation and comparison of different renewable energy types to provide background on existing and emerging technologies for thermal heating and cooling and their respective advantages. Additionally, information on how the Commonwealth\'92s energy resources and regulations factor into the success of the DOER\'92s renewable thermal project sites is provided.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb240\sa120

\b\fs32 \cf0 2.1  Fossil Fuel Dependence and its Consequences\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb60\qj

\b0\fs22 \cf0 The United States has depended on non-renewable resources as a source of power since the 1800\'92s when oil and coal were discovered to be more energy dense than wood (Samimi, & Zarinabadi, 2012, WaitButWhy, 2015). Figure 1 represents the percentages of the total energy consumed in the United States. More than 80% of the total energy consumed by the country comes from a non-renewable source of energy (U.S. Energy Information Administration, 2015). \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi340\sl360\slmult1\sb240\qc
\cf0  \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120\qc

\fs24 \cf0  \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sb120\sa120
